, depression and suicide. In Fistula Politics, Alison Heller illustrates the inaccuracy of these popular narratives and shows how they serve the interests not of the women so affected, but of humanitarian organizations, the media, and local clinics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFistulaxTreatmentzNiger. 0aReproductive healthzNiger. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezNiger. 0aWomenzNigerxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afistula, birth, injuries, Niger, women, Africa, obstetric, fertility, humanitarian, media, clinics, West Africa, pregnancy, health care, medicine.1 aManderson, Lenore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978800403zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978800403423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978800403.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK